00:22:03,572 --> 00:22:05,115
‐ Probably won't.
MRS. WIGFIELD: What's that now?

482
00:22:05,115 --> 00:22:06,283
‐ [clears throat]

483
00:22:06,283 --> 00:22:09,161
‐ I said, you too,
Ms. Wigfield.

484
00:22:09,161 --> 00:22:12,289
SINGER:
♪ Now I'm so glad ♪

485
00:22:12,289 --> 00:22:13,916
‐ [sighs]

486
00:22:13,916 --> 00:22:16,502
‐ All right, Chip,
it's one thing to be sad,

487
00:22:16,502 --> 00:22:18,462
but it's another to be rude
to my customers,

488
00:22:18,462 --> 00:22:19,964
who are also our neighbors.

489
00:22:19,964 --> 00:22:23,259
So leave the attitude behind
when we get to church tonight.

490
00:22:23,259 --> 00:22:24,844
‐ I'm not going to church.

491
00:22:24,844 --> 00:22:28,013
SINGER:
♪ Till she has to go away ♪

492
00:22:28,013 --> 00:22:29,223
DOLORES:
Excuse me?

493
00:22:30,724 --> 00:22:33,269
Oh, you're gonna turn
your back on Jesus?

494
00:22:33,269 --> 00:22:35,187
‐ I'm pretty sure
he turned his back on me.

495
00:22:35,187 --> 00:22:37,189
DOLORES:
I know you're upset, son,

496
00:22:37,189 --> 00:22:40,359
but now, more than ever,
you need prayer

497
00:22:40,359 --> 00:22:42,945
and community, and God.

498
00:22:42,945 --> 00:22:45,114
‐ God?

499
00:22:45,114 --> 00:22:47,741
What kind of God would let
a teenage girl die

500
00:22:47,741 --> 00:22:49,285
in a car accident?

501
00:22:49,285 --> 00:22:51,036
Not one that I need.
I'm done.

502
00:22:59,962 --> 00:23:02,965
<i>[TV narrator</i>
<i>speaking indistinctly]</i>

503
00:23:06,343 --> 00:23:08,345
<i>[meerkats on TV chirping]</i>

504
00:23:10,681 --> 00:23:12,057
WALT: Hey, Miles?

505
00:23:12,057 --> 00:23:14,935
Want to watch a little
<i>Meerkat Manor</i> with us?

506
00:23:14,935 --> 00:23:16,395
‐ It's gotten really good.

507
00:23:16,395 --> 00:23:18,898
Flower just evicted
Kinkaju and Mozart.

508
00:23:18,898 --> 00:23:21,775
WALT: Spoiler alert.
‐ Uh, I‐I'm working.

509
00:23:21,775 --> 00:23:27,114
Trying to finish this essay
for my World Religions class.

510
00:23:27,114 --> 00:23:30,826
Or start it, actually.
It's important.

511
00:23:30,826 --> 00:23:34,997
I'm not really interested
in the domestic issues
of meerkats.

512
00:23:34,997 --> 00:23:36,832
<i>TV narrator:</i>
<i>While the rest</i>
<i>of the Whiskers family</i>

513
00:23:36,832 --> 00:23:39,126
<i>hang out together</i>
<i>in the stolen burrow,</i>

514
00:23:39,126 --> 00:23:41,587
<i>grooming and enjoying</i>
<i>each other's company,</i>

515
00:23:41,587 --> 00:23:43,422
<i>it's a very different story...</i>

516
00:23:43,422 --> 00:23:46,091
‐ I can't write
with you staring at me.

517
00:23:54,558 --> 00:23:56,310
[knock at door]

518
00:23:56,310 --> 00:23:57,770
I'm good.

519
00:23:59,813 --> 00:24:02,733
I‐I'm sorry, I just, uh...

520
00:24:02,733 --> 00:24:05,778
this‐‐this essay
is a big part of my grade,

521
00:24:05,778 --> 00:24:08,072
and I don't even know
what I'm gonna write.

522
00:24:08,072 --> 00:24:13,035
And so... I'm just‐‐I'm just
under a lot of pressure.

523
00:24:16,538 --> 00:24:20,459
‐ Your father and I
want you to know,

524
00:24:20,459 --> 00:24:23,253
you don't have to go back
to Culver Creek.

525
00:24:24,922 --> 00:24:28,676
You can return
to your high school here.

526
00:24:28,676 --> 00:24:30,469
You can come home, Miles.

527
00:24:30,469 --> 00:24:32,763
We'll help you get over it.
‐ I'm not gonna get over it.

528
00:24:32,763 --> 00:24:36,558
JUDY: I didn't mean
right away, of course.

529
00:24:38,268 --> 00:24:41,981
But in time,
you will weather this storm.

530
00:24:46,151 --> 00:24:47,987
‐ Not this one.

531
00:24:50,239 --> 00:24:53,409
If people were rain...

532
00:24:55,536 --> 00:25:00,040
I was drizzle.

533
00:25:00,040 --> 00:25:04,211
And... she...

534
00:25:05,963 --> 00:25:09,258
She was a hurricane, okay?

535
00:25:09,258 --> 00:25:11,719
There's not gonna be
a day in my life

536
00:25:11,719 --> 00:25:14,054
where I don't think about her.

537
00:25:18,434 --> 00:25:22,062
‐ It feels like that now,
but it will get easier.

538
00:25:22,062 --> 00:25:24,565
‐ I don't want it
to get easier!

539
00:25:24,565 --> 00:25:28,235
Because then that means
that I've stopped
remembering her.

540
00:25:28,235 --> 00:25:29,820
And is that what
we're rooting for here?

541
00:25:29,820 --> 00:25:31,363
That‐‐that I forget her?

542
00:25:31,363 --> 00:25:34,241
That she just becomes
some distant memory?

543
00:25:34,241 --> 00:25:36,618
Is that you want me to do
when you die,

544
00:25:36,618 --> 00:25:38,162
for me to forget you?

545
00:25:38,162 --> 00:25:40,956
Because the bodies
are gonna keep on piling up,

546
00:25:40,956 --> 00:25:42,666
and the longer that I live,

547
00:25:42,666 --> 00:25:45,169
the more people that I know
will die.

548
00:25:45,169 --> 00:25:49,548
And do I even have enough space
in my memory for all of them?

549
00:25:49,548 --> 00:25:53,886
And what does it
even matter anyway?

550
00:25:53,886 --> 00:25:57,806
Someday, no one will remember
that she even existed,

551
00:25:57,806 --> 00:25:59,600
or that I did.

552
00:25:59,600 --> 00:26:04,563
Everything falls apart...
memories too.

553
00:26:06,482 --> 00:26:09,902
And then you're left
with nothing,

554
00:26:09,902 --> 00:26:12,404
not even a fucking ghost.

555
00:26:19,536 --> 00:26:21,497
‐ Just think about it.

556
00:26:31,965 --> 00:26:34,968
[phone ringing]

557
00:26:37,596 --> 00:26:40,808
‐ Hello.
<i>MILES: Hey, Colonel.</i>

558
00:26:40,808 --> 00:26:42,810
‐ Merry Christmas Eve, Pudge.

559
00:26:42,810 --> 00:26:45,771
I hope you note
that that was dripping
in irony.

560
00:26:45,771 --> 00:26:47,564
MILES:
Noted.

561
00:26:47,564 --> 00:26:52,277
My ability to understand
sarcasm is still intact.

562
00:26:52,277 --> 00:26:55,614
‐ Good, otherwise,
this friendship is over.

563
00:26:55,614 --> 00:26:58,992
And seeing as though
you are my last
remaining friend,

564
00:26:58,992 --> 00:27:00,410
I can't afford to lose you.

565
00:27:03,956 --> 00:27:08,710
‐ Listen, Colonel, um,
I was talking with my parents.

566
00:27:08,710 --> 00:27:11,463
‐ Walter Halter and Judy.
Send them my best.

567
00:27:11,463 --> 00:27:13,966
‐ Sure, I will.

568
00:27:16,051 --> 00:27:21,974
But, uh, we were
discussing everything,

569
00:27:21,974 --> 00:27:23,809
and...

570
00:27:26,103 --> 00:27:28,313
I'm not going back
to Culver Creek.

571
00:27:28,313 --> 00:27:30,399
<i>I can't.</i>

572
00:27:30,399 --> 00:27:32,359
<i>It's‐‐it's gonna be</i>
<i>spring soon,</i>

573
00:27:32,359 --> 00:27:34,361
<i>and she's not gonna be there</i>
<i>to see it.</i>

574
00:27:34,361 --> 00:27:36,905
And I just...

575
00:27:36,905 --> 00:27:40,284
I‐I don't wanna see a world

576
00:27:40,284 --> 00:27:42,786
she will never get to see.

577
00:27:42,786 --> 00:27:45,789
<i>[somber music]</i>

578
00:27:45,789 --> 00:27:51,336
<i>♪ ♪</i>

579
00:27:51,336 --> 00:27:55,048
‐ Okay, seasons are a thing.

580
00:27:55,048 --> 00:27:56,633
There's no avoiding that.

581
00:27:56,633 --> 00:27:58,552
<i>So, uh, what you gonna do?</i>

582
00:27:58,552 --> 00:28:00,762
‐ Well, my grades were good,

583
00:28:00,762 --> 00:28:03,724
<i>and my teachers</i>
<i>at my old school loved me.</i>

584
00:28:03,724 --> 00:28:06,059
‐ How could they not?

585
00:28:06,059 --> 00:28:10,814
‐ So my parents say
they'll be happy
to have me back.

586
00:28:12,274 --> 00:28:15,277
‐ Well, good.
That's great.

587
00:28:15,277 --> 00:28:18,363
Must be so nice to be able
to run away from your problems

588
00:28:18,363 --> 00:28:20,199
and know everything's
gonna be all right.

589
00:28:21,700 --> 00:28:25,454
I wish you a soft landing,
and good luck.

590
00:28:25,454 --> 00:28:32,419
<i>♪ ♪</i>

591
00:28:56,860 --> 00:28:59,863
<i>[soft folk music]</i>

592
00:28:59,863 --> 00:29:06,495
<i>♪ ♪</i>

593
00:29:23,053 --> 00:29:26,056
SINGER:
♪ Think of you quite often ♪

594
00:29:26,056 --> 00:29:28,225
♪ Wondering how you've been ♪

595
00:29:28,225 --> 00:29:30,644
<i>♪ ♪</i>

596
00:29:30,644 --> 00:29:33,313
[gravel crunching]

597
00:29:33,313 --> 00:29:35,607
♪ Memories are not so bad ♪

598
00:29:35,607 --> 00:29:38,443
♪ They crawl under my skin ♪

599
00:29:38,443 --> 00:29:41,446
<i>♪ ♪</i>

600
00:29:41,446 --> 00:29:43,407
‐ Sorry,
we're closed for tonight.

601
00:29:43,407 --> 00:29:45,492
SINGER:
♪ The last thing
we could picture ♪

602
00:29:45,492 --> 00:29:48,829
♪ You waved to me good‐bye ♪

603
00:29:48,829 --> 00:29:50,914
<i>♪ ♪</i>

604
00:29:50,914 --> 00:29:52,332
‐ What are you doing here?

605
00:29:52,332 --> 00:29:55,294
‐ Dr. Hyde!

606
00:29:55,294 --> 00:29:57,129
SINGER:
♪ I think it's worth a try ♪

607
00:29:57,129 --> 00:29:58,714
‐ You didn't want
to go to church.

608
00:29:58,714 --> 00:30:01,133
Looks like church
did come to you.

609
00:30:01,133 --> 00:30:03,677
SINGER:
♪ 'Cause oh ♪

610
00:30:03,677 --> 00:30:06,513
♪ You are ♪

611
00:30:06,513 --> 00:30:08,765
♪ Such beautiful friends ♪

612
00:30:08,765 --> 00:30:11,018
♪ The beautiful prize ♪

613
00:30:11,018 --> 00:30:12,853
♪ And ♪

614
00:30:12,853 --> 00:30:15,480
♪ All we know ♪

615
00:30:15,480 --> 00:30:17,274
‐ Here we go.

616
00:30:17,274 --> 00:30:18,650
COLONEL:
No, Mom.

617
00:30:18,650 --> 00:30:20,861
I don't want a cookie.

618
00:30:20,861 --> 00:30:22,612
I can't believe you called him.

619
00:30:22,612 --> 00:30:25,198
‐ I can't believe he came.

620
00:30:25,198 --> 00:30:27,117
We're honored
to have you here, Dr. Hyde.

621
00:30:27,117 --> 00:30:29,661
I'ma leave you all alone,
but if you need anything,

622
00:30:29,661 --> 00:30:30,787
you just holler.

623
00:30:30,787 --> 00:30:32,664
‐ Thank you, Dolores.
‐ Thank you.

624
00:30:37,044 --> 00:30:38,337
[door clicks shut]

625
00:30:38,337 --> 00:30:39,713
‐ So...

626
00:30:40,964 --> 00:30:42,674
‐ So...

627
00:30:48,889 --> 00:30:51,808
I understand you're having
a crisis of faith.

628
00:30:51,808 --> 00:30:53,643
‐ No crisis, no faith.

629
00:30:53,643 --> 00:30:55,896
‐ People need to believe
in something, Mr. Martin.

630
00:30:55,896 --> 00:30:57,272
‐ Yeah, well, people are fools.

631
00:30:57,272 --> 00:30:58,940
HYDE:
So you're prepared
to render judgment

632
00:30:58,940 --> 00:31:01,234
on all of humanity?

633
00:31:01,234 --> 00:31:03,403
‐ Just fools.

634
00:31:03,403 --> 00:31:05,405
Look, I appreciate
you coming out here,

635
00:31:05,405 --> 00:31:06,656
but it's not necessary.

636
00:31:06,656 --> 00:31:09,659
I really don't need to hear
no inspirational

637
00:31:09,659 --> 00:31:11,995
"it's all God's plan,"
circle of life bullshit.

638
00:31:11,995 --> 00:31:13,288
‐ That's not why I'm here.

639
00:31:13,288 --> 00:31:14,664
‐ So you're not here
to cheer me up?

640
00:31:14,664 --> 00:31:17,000
‐ I am not.

641
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:19,169
I'm here to be with you.

642
00:31:19,169 --> 00:31:20,921
You're grieving,
so let yourself grieve.

643
00:31:20,921 --> 00:31:22,130
You don't have to fight it.

644
00:31:22,130 --> 00:31:24,674
‐ Well,
maybe I feel like fighting.

645
00:31:24,674 --> 00:31:27,677
Alaska's dead,
Miles isn't coming back,

646
00:31:27,677 --> 00:31:29,763
and I'm spending Christmas Eve
with my teacher.

647
00:31:29,763 --> 00:31:31,098
HYDE:
So be with your anger.

648
00:31:31,098 --> 00:31:33,392
Allow yourself to feel
what you're feeling.

649
00:31:33,392 --> 00:31:35,894
The only hope of getting
to the other side of this

650
00:31:35,894 --> 00:31:37,104
is to go through it,

651
00:31:37,104 --> 00:31:40,065
and I'm here
to go through it with you.

652
00:31:40,065 --> 00:31:43,777
‐ Yeah, well, you're gonna be
sitting here for a long time.

653
00:31:43,777 --> 00:31:46,029
‐ Well, that's all right.
I got no place to be.

654
00:31:51,618 --> 00:31:53,703
It's all right.

655
00:32:03,380 --> 00:32:05,590
It's all right.

656
00:32:06,591 --> 00:32:07,759
It's okay.

657
00:32:07,759 --> 00:32:09,761
‐ [gently sobbing]

658
00:32:11,179 --> 00:32:13,348
HYDE:
It's okay.

659
00:32:13,348 --> 00:32:16,893
‐ [sobbing]

660
00:32:16,893 --> 00:32:18,437
[yells]

661
00:32:18,437 --> 00:32:20,188
HYDE:
It's okay, son.
It's okay.

662
00:32:20,188 --> 00:32:22,274
COLONEL:
[sobbing]

663
00:32:22,274 --> 00:32:26,736
I don't understand
why He has to take my friend.

664
00:32:26,736 --> 00:32:28,196
I just miss my friend.

665
00:32:28,196 --> 00:32:29,448
HYDE:
I know, son.
I know.

666
00:32:29,448 --> 00:32:32,242
Just let it out.
That's good.

667
00:32:32,242 --> 00:32:33,702
I miss her too.

668
00:32:33,702 --> 00:32:36,705
‐ [sobbing]

669
00:32:38,540 --> 00:32:41,376
[Hyde gently shushes]

670
00:32:43,044 --> 00:32:46,047
<i>[solemn music]</i>

671
00:32:46,047 --> 00:32:53,054
<i>♪ ♪</i>

672
00:33:03,607 --> 00:33:10,614
<i>♪ ♪</i>

673
00:33:17,871 --> 00:33:20,957
<i>ALASKA:</i>
<i>"Great Perhaps."</i>

674
00:33:20,957 --> 00:33:22,959
<i>I like it.</i>

675
00:33:22,959 --> 00:33:25,420
<i>It's just ambiguous enough.</i>

676
00:33:25,420 --> 00:33:30,717
<i>Unquantifiable,</i>
<i>kind of magical.</i>

677
00:33:30,717 --> 00:33:32,719
<i>Hell of a metaphor.</i>

678
00:33:32,719 --> 00:33:36,473
<i>♪ ♪</i>

679
00:33:36,473 --> 00:33:38,808
[low chatter]

680
00:33:40,519 --> 00:33:47,400
<i>♪ ♪</i>

681
00:33:57,827 --> 00:34:00,330
‐ So.

682
00:34:00,330 --> 00:34:03,542
Looks like I'm not getting
a single after all.

683
00:34:03,542 --> 00:34:06,211
‐ Sorry to let you down.

684
00:34:06,211 --> 00:34:08,838
‐ You can never let me down,
you skinny bastard.

685
00:34:08,838 --> 00:34:11,841
<i>[uplifting music]</i>

686
00:34:11,841 --> 00:34:17,347
<i>♪ ♪</i>

687
00:34:17,347 --> 00:34:19,766
[bell tolling]

688
00:34:19,766 --> 00:34:21,893
[birds chirping]

689
00:34:24,521 --> 00:34:27,941
EAGLE:
We put a lot of thought
into how best to remember her,

690
00:34:27,941 --> 00:34:30,151
and so I am proud to present

691
00:34:30,151 --> 00:34:33,613
the Alaska Young
memorial bench.

692
00:34:33,613 --> 00:34:36,575
Alaska loved to read,
and so maybe,

693
00:34:36,575 --> 00:34:38,535
with spring upon us,

694
00:34:38,535 --> 00:34:40,704
other students will sit
on her bench,

695
00:34:40,704 --> 00:34:43,999
reading and daring to dream.

696
00:34:43,999 --> 00:34:46,668
[applause]

697
00:34:51,590 --> 00:34:54,676
COLONEL:
A bench.
They gave her a fucking bench?

698
00:34:54,676 --> 00:34:55,844
She would have hated that shit.

699
00:34:55,844 --> 00:34:57,178
LARA:
Well, then get her something

700
00:34:57,178 --> 00:34:58,805
she would have loved.

701
00:34:58,805 --> 00:35:00,974
‐ What, like shitty wine
and pretentious metaphors?

702
00:35:00,974 --> 00:35:04,185
‐ I don't know.
How 'bout a prank?

703
00:35:05,979 --> 00:35:09,107
‐ Yes.
That's great.

704
00:35:09,107 --> 00:35:11,401
A memorial prank.

705
00:35:11,401 --> 00:35:13,653
‐ Alaska Young Memorial Prank.

706
00:35:13,653 --> 00:35:15,655
TAKUMI:
She did have that one idea
she was working on.

707
00:35:15,655 --> 00:35:17,532
She was saving it
for our senior prank.

708
00:35:17,532 --> 00:35:19,618
Never made it out
of the planning phases,

709
00:35:19,618 --> 00:35:20,910
but it's really good.

710
00:35:20,910 --> 00:35:23,330
‐ Executed as designed,
it's more than just good.

711
00:35:23,330 --> 00:35:24,873
It's epic.

712
00:35:24,873 --> 00:35:26,750
But to pull it off,
we gonna need more
than just us.

713
00:35:26,750 --> 00:35:29,669
‐ True, we're gonna need
the whole school,

714
00:35:29,669 --> 00:35:31,630
and we could get in
so much trouble.

715
00:35:31,630 --> 00:35:33,256
‐ I'm in.
LARA: Me too.

716
00:35:33,256 --> 00:35:34,633
‐ Down.
‐ Let's make history.

717
00:35:39,179 --> 00:35:42,182
<i>[Goldfrapp's "Ooh La La"]</i>

718
00:35:42,182 --> 00:35:44,476
<i>♪ ♪</i>

719
00:35:44,476 --> 00:35:46,478
GOLDFRAPP:
♪ Dial up ♪

720
00:35:46,478 --> 00:35:49,814
‐ Hey, man, I can't
give you any more free stuff.

721
00:35:49,814 --> 00:35:51,399
Management was not pleased.

722
00:35:51,399 --> 00:35:53,026
‐ I don't want
a free Ding Dong, Gus.

723
00:35:53,026 --> 00:35:55,820
‐ What you want?
‐ I want you.

724
00:35:55,820 --> 00:35:57,697
‐ Oh, hey.

725
00:35:57,697 --> 00:35:59,574
‐ Sara, I need you.

726
00:35:59,574 --> 00:36:01,576
‐ Please don't do this.

727
00:36:01,576 --> 00:36:04,079
‐ What?
No, not like that.

728
00:36:04,079 --> 00:36:05,330
LONGWELL: What's going on?

